metadata.name: WAR #3
metadata.description:
We are constantly warring, often times with ourselves, sometimes with others, but mostly with what we even don't know. This needs to stop, and it shall stop by the following terms:

I.   We shall never accept wins, depending on others' losses.
II.  We shall never accept life, sucked out of others' deaths.
III. We shall never accept prosperity, originated from others' poverty.
IV.  We shall never accept happiness, sourced from others' misery.
V.   We shall never accept civilization, built upon others' devastation.

metadata.name: Bipole #85
metadata.description:
Two meandering paths are created with opposite flow vectors. The paths are drawn with a twisty drip brush.

Created for #tezos4tezos in May 2022.

Features 
- The amount each stroke's bristles twist as the path is drawn
- If each paths starts off strong or soft
- Splats at the starts and ends of the path
- Dark mode
- Monochrome or colored lines (colors from the p5riso palette)
- Paper fibers in the background
- 10% chance of dark orange and black lines

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 2400px by 1483px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume.

metadata.name: TIMEFRAMES #14
metadata.description:
‘What if you could take a photo of time?’

As a photographer myself, the act of taking photos is the act of freezing moments of time. Moments that will no longer ever be here. Each layer represents not only 3 aspects of time (hours, minutes and seconds) but also a very important aspect of photography: the light. Combining these two instances: the visual interpretation of light and the generative aspect of time - I present ‘TIMEFRAMES’.

12 selected colors. 5,688,900 possible combinations.

The less layers the rarer - ranging from 100% to 18%
All timeframes that have 42 on it like 4:20:00, 4:42:42, 4:20:42 are rarer - ranging from 50% to 42%
The darker the colors the rarer - ranging from 100% to 89%

Click on the image to Download. Created with @PureSpider’s template.

José Gasparian.
2022.

metadata.name: Pencil Lines #33
metadata.description:
This project is a journey to embrace creativity with a programmatic form. As a child, I carried a pencil and paper to mimic the world around me. The paper canvas provided a path to empathize with a world, so I could attempt to better understand it. At some point along the way, I lost touch with the analog medium and found myself taken with the structure of computers and languages. Over time, computers became more of a consumption engine. Almost a year ago, I started on a daily journey of returning to creation with the p5js medium. Today marks my 306th day of that journey. Each day the canvas and I practice what can be. Each day beauty is found and destroyed.

This canvas is generated by varied line strokes and gaps in between. As my practice evolved, patterns began to appear. I watched as the canvas transformed into woven fabric and at other times pencil shading practices. The forms were magical and captivating and thus are both part of this project.

Wishing this project offers as much joy to others as it did for me.

metadata.name: Curlida #110
metadata.description:
Fully generative art. Each token is 100% unique.

Traits:
- 28 color palettes;
- 5 "stylers" - cells filling style;
- 3 "ratio" - aspect ratio.

Press 's' to save png.

High-level description of the algorithm:
Frame is separated into flows using several different Perlin noise generators. 
Frame cells are filled with curves. Each curve is drawn in the direction plotted by noise generator.
Each value returned by the generator at (x, y) is mapped to color from a predefined range.


Made with p5js, math and love by @ivposure

metadata.name: Sprawling Walls #34
metadata.description:
I recall living for quite some time in urban village areas, where they formed within a striking urban setting. Unlike suburban houses where spaces are ample and most housings are planned with careful consideration of other houses, these urban villages are limited by site and geographic boundaries. So it's almost inevitable that houses are built so close with each other, so much that no house has a backyard or front yard, everything was just roof and walls as far as the eye can see. Because these dwellings grow persistently according to the wants and needs of their dwellers, as the families within these walls grow, so does the urban village.

It's a chaotic scene for sure, but urban villages have their own candid beauty. Just by looking from the stacked facades of the walls that made up the houses, we can imagine the warm dynamic between the people and strong living impulses that spark from behind these walls.

metadata.name: looking through a glass #108
metadata.description:
or life is a colorful mess
or not your usual generative forest

this art project continues the path that 'life is a (beautiful) mess' began with the representation of our lives using drawing lines that make repetitive patterns
as life develops, we look at it through the glass of our unique existence. every event, emotion and thought we experience stain our personal glass and conditions our regard towards the world that surrounds us
the cercles in every composition, represents that glass that we all have between us and the world, and the movement of the lines under it, life developing as we observe it
or it's just another figurative generative art project, as you wish...

10 different palettes
over 30 different color pens
single or multiple color glasses or cercles option
press [1], [2], [3], [4] keys to multiply resolution and reload the piece
press [s] to capture an image .png
press [r] to reload the animation
click the mouse to stop the drawing
doubleclick the mouse to resume the drawing

generative art created by mehno using p5js
